============================================================
15. If Application Has REST Resources
============================================================

If application has JAX-RS resource classes like:

@Path("/customer")
public class CustomerResource {
}

add:

<dependency>
    <groupId>jakarta.ws.rs</groupId>
    <artifactId>jakarta.ws.rs-api</artifactId>
    <version>3.1.0</version>
</dependency>

If application only calls downstream REST APIs, Jersey client dependencies are enough.

============================================================
16. If Application Has Servlet Classes
============================================================

Preferably application should not have servlet classes.

If it has filters/interceptors like:

import javax.servlet.Filter;
import javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest;

change to:

import jakarta.servlet.Filter;
import jakarta.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest;

and add:

<dependency>
    <groupId>jakarta.servlet</groupId>
    <artifactId>jakarta.servlet-api</artifactId>
    <version>6.0.0</version>
    <scope>provided</scope>
</dependency>

Recommended:

Move servlet filters to webapp later.
Keep application independent.

============================================================
17. Code Import Changes
============================================================

Change across schema, config, and application:

javax.xml.bind.*     -> jakarta.xml.bind.*
javax.xml.ws.*       -> jakarta.xml.ws.*
javax.jws.*          -> jakarta.jws.*
javax.ws.rs.*        -> jakarta.ws.rs.*
javax.annotation.*   -> jakarta.annotation.*
javax.validation.*   -> jakarta.validation.*
javax.activation.*   -> jakarta.activation.*

Do not change these Java SE packages:

javax.net.ssl.*
javax.crypto.*
javax.security.*
javax.naming.*
javax.sql.*
javax.xml.parsers.*
javax.xml.transform.*
javax.xml.datatype.*
javax.xml.namespace.*
javax.xml.stream.*

Common mistake:

Not every javax package becomes jakarta.
Only Java EE / Jakarta EE packages should be migrated.

============================================================
18. RichFaces / JSF Leakage Check
============================================================

Before compiling application, run:

grep -R "org.richfaces\|javax.faces\|jakarta.faces\|FacesContext\|UIComponent" application/src/main/java

If found, do not add JSF/Faces dependency to application.

Instead, move that class to webapp later.

Bad application code:

import javax.faces.context.FacesContext;
import org.richfaces.event.FileUploadEvent;

Do not keep this in application.

Better approach:

Create an interface in application:

public interface UserNotificationService {
    void showInfo(String message);
    void showError(String message);
}

Application depends only on this interface.

Later, webapp can implement it using JSF / Jakarta Faces.

